Introduction

The Nutri-Score is a simplified nutritional labeling system that classifies foods based on their nutritional quality. It assigns a letter (from A for the healthiest products to E for the least healthy ones) to indicate the overall nutritional value. This system aims to guide consumers in their food choices.

Our study focuses on pizzas, pies, and quiches in the United States, with 3133 observations available. The objective is to provide reliable and relevant information to consumers about the Nutri-Score to enhance their understanding. To achieve this goal, we will conduct an analysis using graphs, tables, and statistics.

Graphs and Statistics

Distribution of Nutri-Score Grades

We observe that the majority of products in the pizza/pie/quiche category are classified as C or D on the Nutri-Score, while products classified as A or E are very rare.

Impact of Lipids on Nutri-Score

Products with more than 40% lipids include pecans, pepperoni packets, or almonds for apple pies, and 0% lipids are not plausible.

After filtering lipids, we notice that the higher the lipid content, the lower the Nutri-Score.

Impact of Carbohydrates on Nutri-Score

The data point with over 79g of carbohydrates represents a lemon meringue pie preparation kit, which does not belong to our product category.

We observe that sugar has little impact on the Nutri-Score for this product category. However, the E category shows a wide variability of values with many sweet products. It is likely that sweet pies are mostly classified as E. Additionally, there is a clustering of very sweet products in D, corresponding to sweet pies.

Impact of Proteins on Nutri-Score

A product in our category with 0g of proteins is not plausible. Furthermore, the value of over 25g of proteins is incorrect, as the pizza packaging indicates 14g of proteins per 119g.

Similar to the above, sweet pies are likely to contain fewer proteins.

Impact of Salt on Nutri-Score

The data point with over 7g of salt is an error, as the sodium quantity was used instead of salt. Additionally, values at 0g are also errors or do not correspond to the category.

We observe that the higher the salt content, the lower the Nutri-Score.

Energy and Nutri-Score

On this graph, we notice that products with lower Nutri-Scores contain more energy. Moreover, sweet pies are significantly higher in energy compared to other products.

Impact of Organic, Vegan, and Palm Oil-Free Attributes on Nutri-Score

We observe that no organic product is classified as Nutri-Score E, and they generally receive better scores.

The same observation applies to vegan products.

Finally, products without palm oil are generally better rated than those with palm oil.

Conclusion

In conclusion, this study highlights the important factors to consider when discussing the Nutri-Score. It is essential to note that our study focuses on pies, quiches, and pizzas. Sugar, salt, proteins, and saturated fatty acids are significant factors in Nutri-Score calculation, which should not be overlooked. We also observed a significant correlation between energy and Nutri-Score. Furthermore, it is worth noting that vegan, organic, and palm oil-free products are indeed rated better for health, with a healthier composition. However, it is necessary to understand that the Nutri-Score is not specific to product categories; some products are inherently intended to be sweet (such as pastries like pies) and will thus inevitably have a lower Nutri-Score.
